<div id="review_3449541869" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3449541869" />
    <a title="Anne" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/108887244-anne"><img alt="Anne" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1579327172p2/108887244.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3449541869?book_show_action=true">Sep 05, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Anne" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Anne" href="/user/show/108887244-anne">Anne</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Audible Audio " href="/book/show/35961885-the-fall-of-the-house-of-usher">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/108887244-anne?shelf=horror">horror</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/108887244-anne?shelf=short-stories">short-stories</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/108887244-anne?shelf=hoopla">hoopla</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/108887244-anne?shelf=boxall-1001-books-the-list">boxall-1001-books-the-list</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/108887244-anne?shelf=classics">classics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/108887244-anne?shelf=boxall-1001-books-read">boxall-1001-books-read</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/108887244-anne?shelf=gothic">gothic</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/108887244-anne?shelf=october-spooky">october-spooky</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/108887244-anne?shelf=audio-great">audio-great</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/108887244-anne?shelf=1800s-1840s">1800s-1840s</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3449541869" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17593214766153035659"><b> “I know not how it was — but, with the first glimpse of the building, a sense of insufferable gloom pervaded my spirit.” </b> <br/><br/><i>The Fall of the House of Usher</i> is an 1839 short story first published in a magazine of which Poe was an editor. Outrightly gothic with all details and events contributing to the plot. And Poe’s poem <i>The Haunted Place</i> appears in the text. <br/><br/>Roderick Usher, a boyhood friend to the unnamed narrator, persuaded his friend to come posthaste for a visit to his ancestral home to lend </span>
  <span id="freeText17593214766153035659" style="display:none"><b> “I know not how it was — but, with the first glimpse of the building, a sense of insufferable gloom pervaded my spirit.” </b> <br /><br /><i>The Fall of the House of Usher</i> is an 1839 short story first published in a magazine of which Poe was an editor. Outrightly gothic with all details and events contributing to the plot. And Poe’s poem <i>The Haunted Place</i> appears in the text. <br /><br />Roderick Usher, a boyhood friend to the unnamed narrator, persuaded his friend to come posthaste for a visit to his ancestral home to lend his cheerfulness because he suffered from severe maladies. When the narrator arrived, he found the house of Usher dark, dreary, oppressive. The house was mostly empty except for a couple of silent staff. He “breathed an atmosphere of sorrow.” Even Roderick’s sister, Madeline, was ill. So, the narrator set about cheering his friend by way of reading aloud, painting, playing music. Not until the peak of a tempest does the narrator realizes the full horror of the situation. <br /><br /> It’s no doubt the writing conjured a vivid image of the house as if it were alive as the themes of madness and isolation built the suspense to a climax. My favorite part was the parallel between what was happening in the story with what the narrator was reading aloud. Both the read aloud and the weather were in perfect sync with the story. This story reminded me of <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/89717.The_Haunting_of_Hill_House" title="The Haunting of Hill House by Shirley Jackson" rel="nofollow noopener">The Haunting of Hill House</a> where the house was thought to be an entity. <br /><br />I listened to a 2017 audio book narrated by Chris Lutkin. His reading style brought a sense of doom and gloom to the story that heightened the creep factor. <br /><br />If you are looking for a spooky story to add on a fall reading list, this would deliver. <br /><br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="17593214766153035659" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


